skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Design and generate Rhei Templates — parameterized, reusable bundles of a plan skeleton, optional state machine, optional settings, and a typed input manifest that can be instantiated with `rhei instantiate` to produce ready-to-execute workspaces. Use when users want to capture a recurring workflow (review loops, release checklists, onboarding, audits) once and instantiate it later with concrete inputs.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:8:Produce a Rhei Template directory — a manifest plus a plan skeleton (and, when needed, a state machine and settings) — that `rhei instantiate` can render into a concrete, executable workspace.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:10:The template writer runs before `rhei instantiate`. It packages a proven workflow; `rhei instantiate` materializes it with user-supplied inputs. It does not replace the plan writer or state machine writer — it composes their outputs into something reusable.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:14:Use this skill when a workflow is going to be instantiated more than once with the same shape but different inputs:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:20:- Any "scaffold a workspace" request where plans and state machines would otherwise be copy-pasted.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:25:- The user only needs a state machine — use `rhei-state-machine-writer` directly.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:47:- Does the workflow fit the built-in `rhei` state machine? If yes, bundle no `states.yaml`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:48:- Does it need a custom machine? If yes, author it via `rhei-state-machine-writer` and bundle it.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:71:When a custom state machine is needed, `states.yaml` is a required generated artifact, not background design notes. Produce the complete YAML file in the template directory, include it in any file-by-file response, and keep the rendered plan's `**States:** <name>` declaration aligned with `states.yaml:name`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:91:- A table of inputs: name, type, default, description.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:92:- A short per-task-kind summary of how each task walks the state machine (a table is usually enough).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:97:Do not inline the state machine diagram here — it belongs in `states.yaml` comments (see below). Link to `states.yaml` from the README.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:105:- Every non-terminal state and the transitions between them.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:107:- Which states are `final`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:112:This lives in the YAML file, not just the README, so anyone reading the state machine sees the picture without a context switch. If the template has no `states.yaml` (i.e., it uses the built-in `rhei` machine), skip this — the built-in is documented elsewhere.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:122:- Re-generate the example any time the template changes state shape, inputs, or the default rendering of the seed files.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:124:Pick inputs that exercise every non-trivial code path in the template — e.g., if there's a `focus_areas` input and an empty-list branch, set it to a non-empty list in the example so the rendered output demonstrates the branch. If one example can't reasonably cover every branch, pick the most interesting combination and note the trade-off in the example's README.
