docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:148:- **`"nonzero"`**: matches any non-zero exit code not already matched by a more specific transition from the same source state.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:152:When a program exits and has not already advanced the task (via `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`):
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:154:1. Collect all transitions from the current state that declare an `exit_code` field.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:156:3. If no specific match and the exit code is non-zero, evaluate `"nonzero"` transitions.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:157:4. If exactly one transition matches, fire it (with its `on_leave`/`on_enter` callbacks).
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:158:5. If multiple transitions match at the same specificity level, also evaluate `condition` fields to disambiguate. If still ambiguous after conditions, it is a validation error.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:159:6. If no transition matches and exit code is `0`, log a warning: `warning: program exited 0 but task {id} did not advance from '{state}'`.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:160:7. If no transition matches and exit code is non-zero, log an error and apply the `--continue-on-error` policy.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:164:Programs may also call `rhei transition` or `rhei complete` directly via subprocess invocation, just like agents. When a program does so, the task state changes before the program exits, and exit-code evaluation is skipped entirely — the explicit transition takes precedence.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:166:If a transition from a program state has no `exit_code` field, it is available for manual invocation (`rhei transition`) or for the program to call directly, but it will never be selected by exit-code evaluation.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:168:This allows hybrid approaches where a program handles the common case via exit codes and calls `rhei transition` for edge cases that need more nuanced routing.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:199:Program timeout uses the same SIGTERM → 10 s grace → SIGKILL sequence and the same timeout-transition evaluation as agent timeout. See [Agents Specification — Timeout Behavior](rhei-agents.spec.md#timeout-behavior) for the full step-by-step. The only program-specific differences are:
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:204:Timeout transitions fire with `triggeredBy: 'system'`. See [Transitions Specification — Agent Timeout Trigger](rhei-transitions.spec.md#6-agent-timeout-trigger-triggeredby-system) for the transition selection rules.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:261:Within the sequential execution loop (see [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md#sequential-mode-default---parallel-1)):
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:269:7. Re-read the plan from disk. Check whether the task's state changed — `rhei transition` and `rhei complete` are file-mutating operations that write the new state directly to the plan file.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:270:8. If state changed, log the transition and continue the loop.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:271:9. If state did not change, evaluate exit-code transitions.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:272:10. If an exit-code transition matches, fire it and continue.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:277:Programs respect the same independence rules as agents in parallel mode. Independent tasks with program states can run concurrently up to `--parallel N`.
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:285:| `--no-program` | Suppresses program spawning; fall back to callback-only advancement |
docs/specs/rhei-programs.spec.md:286:| `--parallel <N>` | Programs respect the same independence and concurrency rules as agents |
