docs/overview.md:3:Rhei is a structured markdown plan system for hierarchical task management. It enables parsing, validation, execution, and rendering of Rhei plans with support for formal state transitions.
docs/overview.md:75:Tasks progress through defined **states** (for example `draft` → `pending` → `agent-review` → `completed`). The state machine can be:
docs/overview.md:78:- Formal: Full transition rules with callbacks for automation
docs/overview.md:90:| [Formal State Transitions](formal-state-transitions.md) | Advanced state machine with transitions, callbacks, and multi-platform integration |
docs/overview.md:133:| `rhei-validator` | Validates dependencies, states, cycles, and child task id numbering |
docs/overview.md:134:| `rhei-output` | Renders AST to JSON, GitHub markdown, terminal progress |
docs/overview.md:166:// 2. Load state machine
docs/overview.md:182:For workflows requiring automation, Rhei supports formal state transitions with callbacks. This enables:
docs/overview.md:184:- Declarative transition rules in YAML
docs/overview.md:185:- Pre/post transition callbacks (`on_leave`, `on_enter`)
docs/overview.md:186:- Conditional transitions and timeouts
docs/overview.md:189:See [Formal State Transitions](formal-state-transitions.md) for:
docs/overview.md:191:- [`TransitionContext`](formal-state-transitions.md#transitioncontext-data-structure) — Data passed to callbacks
docs/overview.md:192:- [YAML State Machine Format](formal-state-transitions.md#yaml-state-machine-format-specification) — Configuration schema
docs/overview.md:193:- [Platform Examples](formal-state-transitions.md#example-2-cli-integration-with-bash-functions) — CLI, JavaScript, Python, Java integrations
docs/overview.md:202:- `.yaml` — States and state machine definitions
