docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:3:A hands-on run of the `rhei` CLI exercising the main user-visible workflows: `templates`/`instantiate`, `validate`, `render`, `next`, `transition`, `complete`, `reset`, `run --dry-run`, and `install-skills`. Findings are grouped by severity. Line/command citations use the released binary built from the current `master` branch.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:19:The task is not blocked — it is in `pending`, which has four outgoing transitions (`agent-review`, `human-review`, `completed`, `cancelled`). `rhei next` cannot auto-pick because the choice requires human/agent judgment, but the error tells the user the opposite ("no tasks are ready"). A user can't tell from this message whether:
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:20:- (a) every task is in a terminal state (nothing left to do),
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:21:- (b) every ready task has ambiguous outgoing transitions (use `rhei transition`), or
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:24:**Fix direction:** When `next` finds eligible tasks but can't decide, say so explicitly and list the candidate transitions plus the `rhei transition …` command line to pick one. Reserve "no tasks are ready" for the genuine no-candidates case.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:42:### 3. `rhei transition` checks transition legality before state mismatch
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:46:× transition from 'pending' to 'pending' is not allowed by the state machine
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:53:### 4. `rhei complete` on a non-terminal loop state gives an unactionable error
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:58:× transition from 'fix' to 'completed' is blocked by loop budget or condition
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:61:"Loop budget or condition" is developer-vocabulary. A user/agent receiving this has no signal about what to do next (advance the visit count? finish the current cycle? override?). The error should name the specific condition (`visitCount < visits` with `visitCount=1, visits=2`) and point at the transition(s) that *are* currently available from `fix`.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:83:**Fix direction:** accumulate multiple parse errors per run. The existing validator already does this (cycles + missing deps + state-check in one pass); the parser should match.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:85:### 7. `instantiate` does not validate `type: path` inputs
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:110:### 9. `rhei transition` silently creates a result file with no body
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:112:After `rhei transition … --from pending --to completed` with no `--result` argument:
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:118:The file is created but contains only a header; it is not linked from the task body (only `rhei complete` adds the `> **Result:** …` link). The user ends up with a workspace where some tasks have linked results and others have orphaned `.md` files in `runtime/results/`. This is confusing and surprising — users expect the result file to be an artifact of `complete`, not `transition`.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:120:**Fix direction:** pick one — either `transition` should not touch `runtime/results/`, or it should also insert the link. Current halfway state is the worst of both.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:134:State-machine `instructions` in `.agents/rhei/templates/spec-review/states.yaml` contain literal `{visit_count} < {visits}` strings. `rhei next` prints them verbatim:
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:136:…immediately transition back to `review` when `1 < 2`;
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:137:otherwise transition to `completed`.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:139:`{task_id}` and `{visit_count}` *are* interpolated (visible in the output above), but the boolean-looking `{visit_count} < {visits}` is meant as human-readable explanation, not evaluated. A reader can't easily tell which of these are live variables versus instructional pseudocode. Worth a convention in the docs, or a distinct delimiter for live substitution.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:143:Printed in the human-mode `next` output, the `(default)` parenthetical reads like "codex is the default agent." In fact it means `model=default`, with the agent being explicitly `codex` (set by the state machine). Rewriting as `Agent: codex | Model: default` — or better, showing the two on separate lines — removes the ambiguity.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:162:`(built-in default)` in parentheses after "from" scans like unreplaced template text. "using the built-in default state machine" reads cleanly.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:183:- `rhei states` is a genuinely useful introspection tool — one command to see the whole state machine, transitions, and per-state instructions/artifacts.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:184:- `rhei validate` catches cycles, self-dependencies, missing prerequisites, and missing state lines with clear messages. The validator is noticeably more mature than the parser on the "report multiple problems" axis.
docs/pm-review-2026-04-22.md:185:- `rhei instantiate --list-inputs` is a nice UX for users discovering a template. Keep.
