    90	
    91	### Validation Rules
    92	
    93	- `profiles` must be present and non-empty. Each entry must declare `initial`
    94	  (a state name) and `allowed` (a list of state names). See
    95	  [Profiles](#profiles) for per-profile validation.
    96	- `node_policy.root` and `node_policy.default` are required and must name
    97	  defined profiles. `node_policy.by_type`, when present, maps each declared
    98	  non-root node kind to a defined profile. `node_policy.overrides`, when
    99	  present, is an ordered list of `{match, profile}` entries. See
   100	  [Node Policy](#node-policy) for resolution and validation rules.
   101	- A state definition must not declare `initial: true`. The initial state is
   102	  a property of each profile, not of the state itself.
   103	- `state.target`, when present, must be a non-empty string matching one of:
   104	  `<agent>:<model>`, `<agent>[<mode>]:<model>`,
   105	  `<agent>:<provider>:<model>`, or
   106	  `<agent>[<mode>]:<provider>:<model>`.
   107	- `state.all_targets`, when present, must be a non-empty list of unique
   108	  selectors following the same grammar as `state.target`.
   109	- `state.target` and `state.all_targets` are mutually exclusive.
   110	- `state.target` and `state.all_targets` must not be combined with any of
   111	  `state.model`, `state.all_models`, `state.agent`, or `state.agent_mode`.
   112	- In a target selector, `<agent>` must resolve against the merged `agents`
   113	  registry at validation time.
   114	- In a target selector, `<mode>`, when present, must be a non-empty string and
   115	  must match a key in the resolved agent's `modes` map when that map exists.
   116	- In a target selector, `<provider>`, when present, must be a non-empty string.
   117	- In a target selector, `<model>` must be a non-empty string.
   118	- `models`, when present, must be a list of unique non-empty strings naming model profiles defined in settings.
   119	- `state.model`, when present, must match an entry from the machine-level `models` list.
   120	- `state.all_models`, when present, must be a list of unique non-empty strings drawn from the machine-level `models` list.
   121	- A state must not declare both `all_models: [..]` and `model: <name>`.
   122	- `state.all_models: []` is treated the same as omitting the field.
   123	- `state.visits`, when present, must be an integer greater than or equal to `1`.
   124	- `state.agent`, when present, must be a non-empty string id. Object-valued `agent:` entries are rejected: define the custom agent in the `agents` registry in `settings.json` and reference it by id. The id must resolve against the merged `agents` registry at run time (built-ins → global → project).
   125	- `state.agent` on a `final: true` state is a validation error (terminal states have no work to execute).
   126	- `state.agent` on a `gating: true` state is a validation warning (gating states are human-only; the agent will never be invoked by `rhei run`).
   127	- `state.agent_mode`, when present, must be a non-empty string and requires `state.agent` to be set. The mode name must match a key in the resolved agent's `modes` map, or the agent must declare no modes. See [Agents Specification — Mode Resolution Order](rhei-agents.spec.md#mode-resolution-order).
   128	- `state.agent_timeout`, when present, must be a valid duration string (e.g., `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`).
   129	- A state must not declare both `agent` and `program`.
   130	- `state.program`, when present, must be a non-empty string or a valid program object with at least a `command` field. See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md).
   131	- `state.program` on a `final: true` state is a validation error (terminal states have no work to execute).
   132	- `state.program` on a `gating: true` state is a validation error (gating states require human action; programs execute autonomously).
   133	- `state.program_timeout`, when present, must be a valid duration string (e.g., `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`).
   134	- `state.inputs` / `state.outputs`, when present, must be arrays of unique artifact definitions keyed by `name`.
   135	- Artifact `path` values must be relative to the plan's execution root (the plan-file directory for a single-file plan, or the workspace root for a directory workspace; see [main spec — State Artifact Contracts](../rhei.spec.md#10-state-artifact-contracts)) and must not escape that root after template expansion.
   136	- `artifact.optional`, when present, must be a boolean. Only valid on `inputs` entries; declaring `optional: true` on an `outputs` entry is a validation error (required outputs are always enforced).
   137	- An `optional: true` input that is missing does not block state entry. Its `{input.<name>.exists}` variable resolves to `false` and its `{input.<name>.path}` resolves to the declared path regardless.
   138	- `state.mcp_servers` / `state.skills`, when present, must be arrays. Each entry is either a non-empty string (registry id) or an object with at least an `id` field plus the inline definition fields accepted by the corresponding settings registry.
   139	- Every string id and every `id` field in an inline entry must be unique within the state's list for that kind.
   140	- Every registry id in `state.mcp_servers` must resolve in the merged `mcp_servers` settings registry. Every id in `state.skills` must resolve in the merged `skills` registry. Inline entries do not require a registry match.
   141	- An `mcp_servers` or `skills` entry may declare `optional: true` (default `false`). When `optional: true`, a failure to start the server or locate the skill at spawn time does not block the agent; when `false`, it does. See [Agents Specification — Missing Tooling](rhei-agents.spec.md#missing-tooling).
   142	- `state.mcp_servers` and `state.skills` on a `gating: true` state are a validation error (gating states are human-only; the agent will never be invoked).
   143	- `state.mcp_servers` and `state.skills` on a state with `program:` set are a validation error (programs execute deterministically and do not consume tool surfaces).
   144	- `state.mcp_servers: []` and `state.skills: []` are valid and mean "clear the inherited `defaults` tooling for this state" — not "ignore the field".
   145	- `state.poll`, when present, must be an object with `interval` (a valid duration string, e.g. `30s`, `5m`, `1h`) and `max_attempts` (an integer ≥ `1`).
   146	- `state.poll` on a `final: true` state is a validation error (terminal states have no work to execute).
   147	- `state.poll` on a `gating: true` state is a validation error (gating states require human action; polling executes autonomously).
   148	- `state.poll` combined with `state.visits` is a validation error. `poll.max_attempts` replaces the `visits` cap for the poll state and populates the same `stateVisits` counter.
   149	- A state that declares `poll` must have at least one self-loop transition (`from: <state>, to: <state>`); without it the "retry" branch is unreachable.
   150	
   151	Counted-loop counters are task-instance data, not state-definition data. The state machine declares the cap with `visits`; runtimes persist the current per-task counts in task metadata and mirror the active visit in markdown by appending `-<n>` to `**State:**` for visits greater than `1`.
   152	
   153	When a state declares `all_targets` and `visits`, the engine runs the state
   154	once per listed target and each target-specific execution tracks its own visit
   155	budget. The same scoping rule applies to `all_models`.
   156	
   157	## Polling States
   158	
   159	A state marked with a `poll:` block is a *time-triggered* state: on each attempt
   160	the state's `agent` or `program` runs once, the engine evaluates transitions,
   161	and a self-loop transition is interpreted as "not done yet, come back in
   162	`interval`". This is useful for waiting on external systems (CI runs,
   163	deployments, review approvals exposed over an API) without occupying a
   164	`--parallel` slot during the wait.
   165	
   166	### Shape
   167	
   168	```yaml
   169	states:
   170	  ci-wait:
   171	    description: Wait for the remote CI run to finish.
   172	    program: ".rhei/check-ci.sh"
   173	    poll:
   174	      interval: 5m
   175	      max_attempts: 12
   176	```
   177	
   178	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   179	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   180	| `interval` | duration string | Yes | Minimum wall-clock wait between attempts (e.g., `30s`, `5m`, `1h`). The `--parallel` slot is released during the wait. |
   181	| `max_attempts` | integer | Yes | Upper bound on total attempts for this state within one task lifetime. Must be ≥ `1`. |
   182	
   183	### Semantics
   184	
   185	- **Attempt counter.** `poll.max_attempts` replaces the `visits` cap for the state. The same `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<state-name>` counter records attempts; the counter starts at `1` on first entry and increments on every self-loop re-entry, identical to the `visits` accounting in [Transitions Specification — Counted Loops](rhei-transitions.spec.md#counted-loops).
   186	- **Retry signal.** Any self-loop transition (`from: X, to: X`) selected by the normal transition-matching rules is interpreted as "not done yet." The engine persists `metadata.tasks.<id>.pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name> = now() + interval`, releases the slot, and stops working this task for this pass. On later passes the task is excluded from the ready set until `pollNextAttemptAt` has elapsed.
   187	- **Exit.** Any non-self-loop transition exits the state normally and clears both `pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name>` and `stateVisits.<state-name>` for that state.
   188	- **Exhaustion.** When `stateVisits.<state-name> >= poll.max_attempts`, the engine will *not* execute a self-loop transition even if one matches. Instead it re-evaluates transitions and picks the first matching non-self-loop. The recommended pattern is an explicit exhaustion transition:
   189	  ```yaml
   190	  - from: ci-wait
   191	    to: ci-gave-up
   192	    condition: pollAttempts >= pollMaxAttempts
   193	  ```
   194	  If no non-self-loop matches after exhaustion, the task remains in its current state and `rhei run` aborts the task with a clear error (same behavior as "no matching transition found").
   195	
   196	### Variables for transition conditions
   197	
   198	Polling states expose two additional names alongside the existing `visitCount`
   199	and `visits`:
   200	
   201	- `pollAttempts` — alias for `visitCount` in a poll state (the current attempt index, `1`-based).
   202	- `pollMaxAttempts` — alias for `poll.max_attempts`.
   203	
   204	Both names are available only on transitions whose `from` state declares
   205	`poll:`. Outside a poll state they are undefined.
   206	
   207	### Interaction with other state features
   208	
   209	- **`agent` / `program`.** `poll` works for both. The attempt is one subprocess invocation whose exit code / outputs drive transition matching as usual.
   210	- **`all_targets` / `all_models`.** Fanout composes: each per-target or per-model execution tracks its own `stateVisits.<state-name>` entry (same scoping as `visits`). Slot release applies per fanout invocation.
   211	- **`concurrent`.** Independent: a `concurrent: true` poll state may have multiple tasks in flight simultaneously, each with its own `pollNextAttemptAt`.
   212	- **`agent_timeout` / `program_timeout`.** Bound one attempt's duration; they do not bound the total polling wall-clock time. Combine with `max_attempts` to bound the total.
   213	
   214	## Artifact Contracts
   215	
   216	States may declare required file artifacts as explicit contracts. This lets a
   217	workflow say "review must produce findings" or "fix cannot begin until findings
   218	exist" in machine-readable form rather than relying on prose instructions.
   219	
   220	Each artifact definition has this shape:
   221	
   222	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   223	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   224	| `name` | string | Yes | Stable identifier for the artifact within that state |
   225	| `path` | string | Yes | Workspace-relative file path template |
   226	| `description` | string | No | Human-readable explanation of what the artifact contains |
   227	| `optional` | boolean | No | When `true`, a missing file does not block state entry. Only valid on `inputs` entries. Default: `false`. |
   228	
   229	Supported path template variables:
   230	
   231	- `{task_id}` - the current task id as rendered in the plan
   232	- `{state}` - the canonical unsuffixed state name
   233	- `{visit_count}` - the current visit number for counted-loop states (only available when the state declares `visits`)
   234	- `{target}` - the current execution target selector (only available when the state declares `target` or `all_targets`)
   235	- `{target.slug}` - a filesystem-safe slug derived from `{target}` (only available when the state declares `target` or `all_targets`)
   236	- `{agent}` - the current agent id (available when resolved from `target`, `agent`, or settings)
   237	- `{agent.mode}` - the current agent mode (only available when resolved from `target` or `agent_mode`)
   238	- `{model}` - the current model identifier (available when resolved from `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`)
   239	- `{model.provider}` - the resolved provider id for the current model profile
   240	- `{model.name}` - the resolved provider model name for the current model profile
   241	
   242	Runtime semantics:
   243	
   244	- `inputs` are checked before entering the state and before work begins in that
   245	  state. If any required (`optional: false`, the default) input file is missing,
   246	  the transition is rejected. Optional inputs (`optional: true`) are not checked;
   247	  entry proceeds regardless of whether the file exists.
   248	- `outputs` are checked after callbacks complete and before the transition out
   249	  of the state is committed. If any required output file is missing, the
   250	  transition is rejected.
   251	- For every declared input — required or optional — the engine resolves the path
   252	  and checks whether the file exists. The result is exposed as:
   253	  - `{input.<name>.exists}` template variable: `true` or `false`.
   254	  - `RHEI_INPUT_<NAME>_EXISTS` environment variable for programs: `true` or `false`
   255	    (name uppercased, hyphens and spaces replaced with underscores).
   256	- Artifact contracts are file-existence contracts in v1. They do not yet define
   257	  JSON schemas, required headings, or content-level validation.
   258	- Under `orchestrator` [Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority),
   259	  the `outputs:` existence check doubles as the state's deterministic completion
   260	  signal: the subprocess exit alone is not sufficient, and a zero-exit with any
   261	  missing required output leaves the task in its current state. See
   262	  [Completion Condition](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-condition).
   263	
   264	Example:
   265	
   266	```yaml
   267	states:
   268	  agent-review:
   269	    description: Review the implementation and record concrete findings
   270	    inputs:
   271	      - name: implementation-summary
   272	        path: runtime/results/{task_id}.md
   273	        description: Result written by the implementation step
   274	    outputs:
   275	      - name: findings
   276	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}.md
   277	        description: Review findings for the task
   278	
   279	  agent-review-fix:
   280	    description: Address reviewer findings without changing scope
   281	    inputs:
   282	      - name: findings
   283	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}.md
   284	        description: Findings produced by `agent-review`
   285	```
   286	
   287	### Optional Inputs
   288	
   289	Optional inputs are declared with `optional: true`. The engine does not block
   290	state entry when an optional input is absent, but still resolves the path and
   291	exposes `{input.<name>.exists}` so the agent or program can branch on presence.
   292	
   293	```yaml
   294	states:
   295	  implement:
   296	    description: Implement the task, incorporating prior-iteration notes when available.
   297	    agent: claude-code
   298	    inputs:
   299	      - name: continuation-notes
   300	        path: runtime/continuation/{task_id}.md
   301	        optional: true
   302	        description: Notes written by the check-continue program on the previous loop iteration.
   303	    instructions: |
   304	      Implement Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   305	
   306	      {if input.continuation-notes.exists}
   307	      A previous iteration left the following notes. Read
   308	      `{input.continuation-notes.path}` before starting and address any
   309	      outstanding issues it identifies.
   310	      {else}
   311	      This is the first iteration. Start from the task description above.
   312	      {endif}
   313	
   314	      When finished, transition to `check-continue`.
   315	```
   316	
   317	When `continuation-notes` is absent (first loop iteration), the resolved
   318	instructions become:
   319	
   320	```text
   321	Implement Task 4: Add retry logic.
   322	
   323	This is the first iteration. Start from the task description above.
   324	
   325	When finished, transition to `check-continue`.
   326	```
   327	
   328	When it is present (subsequent iterations):
   329	
   330	```text
   331	Implement Task 4: Add retry logic.
   332	
   333	A previous iteration left the following notes. Read
   334	`runtime/continuation/4.md` before starting and address any
   335	outstanding issues it identifies.
   336	
   337	When finished, transition to `check-continue`.
   338	```
   339	
   340	The surrounding blank lines are preserved when the block is included and
   341	collapsed to a single blank line when it is removed, so the output is clean in
   342	both cases.
   343	
   344	## Template Variables in Instructions and Personality
   345	
   346	The `instructions` and `personality` fields support template variable substitution. Variables use the same `{variable}` syntax as artifact path templates. `rhei next` resolves all template variables before printing output, so agents receive fully expanded prompts with no manual variable resolution required.
   347	
   348	### Variable Namespace
   349	
   350	| Variable | Source | Description | Example Value |
   351	|----------|--------|-------------|---------------|
   352	| `{task_id}` | claimed task | Task identifier as rendered in the plan | `3`, `setup` |
   353	| `{task_title}` | claimed task | Task title text | `Implement caching layer` |
   354	| `{state}` | state machine | Canonical unsuffixed state name | `review` |
   355	| `{visit_count}` | runtime counter | Current visit number for counted-loop states | `2` |
   356	| `{visits}` | state definition | Configured loop budget for the state | `3` |
   357	| `{target}` | target selector | Current execution target selector (requires `target` or `all_targets`) | `codex[yolo]:openai:gpt-5-codex` |
   358	| `{target.slug}` | target selector | Filesystem-safe slug derived from the current target selector | `codex-yolo-openai-gpt-5-codex` |
   359	| `{model}` | model selector | Current model identifier (requires `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`) | `impl-fast` |
   360	| `{model.provider}` | model selector | Resolved provider id for the current model profile | `anthropic` |

