   366	| `{input.<name>.path}` | artifact contract | Resolved path of a declared input artifact | `runtime/results/3.md` |
   367	| `{input.<name>.exists}` | artifact contract | Whether the input artifact file exists on disk at resolution time | `true`, `false` |
   368	| `{output.<name>.path}` | artifact contract | Resolved path of a declared output artifact | `runtime/findings/3.md` |
   369	| `{mcp.<name>.available}` | tooling | Whether the MCP server with id `<name>` started successfully and is attached to the current agent | `true`, `false` |
   370	| `{skill.<id>.available}` | tooling | Whether the skill with id `<id>` is enabled for the current agent | `true`, `false` |
   371	| `{meta.<key>}` | task metadata | Value from the task's YAML metadata section | `alice`, `2` |
   372	
   373	### Resolution Rules
   374	
   375	- **Resolve at output time, not load time.** Template variables are expanded by `rhei next` when printing instructions to an agent. The state machine YAML remains portable — the same `states.yaml` works across different plans.
   376	- **Fail-open on unknown variables.** An unrecognized variable like `{foo}` is left verbatim in the output. This avoids breaking existing instructions that happen to contain braces and makes templates forward-compatible with future variables.
   377	- **Pure substitution, no expressions.** Templates produce text, not decisions. Conditional logic belongs in transition `condition` fields, not in instructions. The resolved text tells the agent "you are on pass 2 of 3" — the agent reads that to decide what to do.
   378	- **Artifact references create a single source of truth.** Using `{input.<name>.path}` or `{output.<name>.path}` instead of repeating raw paths means the artifact contract defines the path once. If the path changes, instructions stay correct automatically.
   379	- **`{visit_count}` and `{visits}` are only meaningful for counted-loop states.** For states without a `visits` declaration, `{visits}` is left unresolved and `{visit_count}` resolves to `1`.
   380	- **`{target}` and `{target.slug}` are only available for target-based execution.** For states that use the legacy `model` / `all_models` fields, `{target}` is left unresolved.
   381	- **Conditional blocks suppress whole paragraphs.** Use `{if input.<name>.exists}`, `{if mcp.<name>.available}`, or `{if skill.<id>.available}` … `{endif}` to include a block of text only when the referenced artifact, server, or skill is present. Use `{else}` between the opening tag and `{endif}` for an alternative block. The entire block — including surrounding blank lines — is removed from the output when the condition is false. Conditional blocks may not be nested in v1.
   382	
   383	### Example
   384	
   385	```yaml
   386	states:
   387	  review:
   388	    description: Review pass that appends findings to a shared artifact.
   389	    instructions: |
   390	      You are on review pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   391	
   392	      Review the current task output and append one numbered review pass to
   393	      `{output.review-notes.path}`.
   394	
   395	      After each review pass, transition to `fix`.
   396	    visits: 2
   397	    outputs:
   398	      - name: review-notes
   399	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   400	
   401	  fix:
   402	    description: Fix step that consumes the review artifact.
   403	    instructions: |
   404	      Fix pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
   405	
   406	      Read `{input.review-notes.path}`, extract the accumulated review
   407	      findings, and update `{output.fix-notes.path}`.
   408	
   409	      If there is another review pass remaining (you are in pass
   410	      {visit_count} of {visits}), transition back to `review`. Once every
   411	      review-fix cycle is complete, transition to `completed`.
   412	    visits: 2
   413	    inputs:
   414	      - name: review-notes
   415	        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
   416	    outputs:
   417	      - name: fix-notes
   418	        path: runtime/fixes/task-{task_id}-fix-{visit_count}.md
   419	```
   420	
   421	When `rhei next` claims Task 3 ("Implement caching layer") during the second visit to `fix`, the agent receives:
   422	
   423	```text
   424	Fix pass 2 of 2 for Task 3: Implement caching layer.
   425	
   426	Read `runtime/reviews/task-3-review-2.md`, extract the accumulated review
   427	findings, and update `runtime/fixes/task-3-fix-2.md`.
   428	
   429	Transition back to `review` if 2 < 2.
   430	Otherwise, transition to `completed`.
   431	```
   432	
   433	### Multi-Target Example
   434	
   435	```yaml
   436	states:
   437	  review:
   438	    description: Independent review by each target
   439	    personality: |
   440	      You are reviewing as {agent} in mode {agent.mode} for target {target}.
   441	      Provide a review from your perspective.
   442	      Do not attempt to emulate or defer to another target's style.
   443	    instructions: |
   444	      Review the implementation for Task {task_id}.
   445	      Read `{input.implementation.path}` and write your findings to
   446	      `{output.findings.path}`.
   447	    all_targets:
   448	      - claude-code[yolo]:anthropic:claude-opus-4-7
   449	      - gemini[yolo]:google:gemini-3.1-pro-preview
   450	      - codex[yolo]:openai:gpt-5-codex
   451	    inputs:
   452	      - name: implementation
   453	        path: runtime/results/{task_id}.md
   454	    outputs:
   455	      - name: findings
   456	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}-{target.slug}.md
   457	```
   458	
   459	Here `{target}` and `{target.slug}` appear in both the instructions and the
   460	artifact path. The artifact contract defines the per-target output path once;
   461	instructions reference it by name.
   462	
   463	Recommended authoring pattern for heterogeneous multi-target runs:
   464	
   465	- Declare one shared state with `all_targets` instead of cloning one state per
   466	  target.
   467	- Use `{target.slug}` in output artifact paths so each execution writes to a
   468	  distinct file, for example `runtime/findings/{task_id}-{target.slug}.md`.
   469	- Prefer the full selector form `<agent>[<mode>]:<provider>:<model>` when the
   470	  workflow depends on all four dimensions. Shorter forms are valid when some
   471	  dimensions are intentionally omitted.
   472	- Add a later synthesis state that consumes the per-target artifacts and writes
   473	  one final document.
   474	
   475	## Agent Field
   476	
   477	States can declare which coding agent transport executes work in that state. The
   478	`agent` field is always a string id. Rhei resolves the id against the merged
   479	`agents` registry — the built-in agents (`claude-code`, `codex`, `gemini`,
   480	`kilocode`, `cursor`) plus any entries declared in
   481	`~/.config/rhei/settings.json` and `<plan-root>/.rhei/settings.json`. Inline
   482	object-shaped agent definitions are not accepted on a state; a custom agent
   483	must be declared in the registry first.
   484	
   485	The optional `agent_mode` field selects a named flag set from the resolved
   486	agent's `modes` map. See [Agents Specification — Modes](rhei-agents.spec.md#modes)
   487	for the common `yolo` / `safe` conventions and the full mode resolution order.
   488	
   489	```yaml
   490	states:
   491	  draft:
   492	    description: Task requires analysis before execution.
   493	    model: impl-deep
   494	    agent: claude-code
   495	    agent_timeout: 15m
   496	
   497	  pending:
   498	    description: Task is ready for implementation.
   499	    model: impl-fast
   500	    agent: claude-code
   501	    agent_mode: yolo
   502	    agent_timeout: 30m
   503	
   504	  agent-review:
   505	    description: A separate reviewing agent inspects the result.
   506	    model: review-deep
   507	    agent: codex
   508	    agent_mode: safe
   509	    agent_timeout: 20m
   510	
   511	  agent-review-fix:
   512	    description: The implementing agent addresses reviewer findings.
   513	    model: impl-fast
   514	    agent: claude-code
   515	    agent_timeout: 30m
   516	
   517	  human-review:
   518	    gating: true
   519	    # No agent - humans act here
   520	
   521	  completed:
   522	    final: true
   523	  cancelled:
   524	    final: true
   525	```
   526	
   527	When `agent` is set on a state, `rhei run` spawns that agent transport to
   528	execute work. When `agent` is omitted, `rhei run` falls back to project-level
   529	or global-level `defaults.agent`. See
   530	[Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) for full resolution order,
   531	invocation profiles, modes, and timeout handling.
   532	
   533	The `model` field names a model profile, which resolves to a provider/model
   534	combo in settings. The `agent` field is an optional transport for autonomous
   535	execution. Either can be set independently at any configuration level, and the
   536	resolution merges across levels.
   537	
   538	## Program States
   539	
   540	States can declare a deterministic program to execute instead of spawning an AI agent. The `program` field names a command (string form) or provides a structured command definition (object form). Program states are the right choice for build, test, lint, deploy, and other steps where the behavior is fixed and an AI agent adds no value.
   541	
   542	```yaml
   543	states:
   544	  build:
   545	    description: Build the project
   546	    program: "make build"
   547	    program_timeout: 10m
   548	
   549	  test:
   550	    description: Run the test suite
   551	    program:
   552	      command: ["npm", "test", "--", "--coverage"]
   553	      env:
   554	        NODE_ENV: test
   555	    program_timeout: 15m
   556	    outputs:
   557	      - name: coverage
   558	        path: coverage/lcov.info
   559	
   560	  deploy:
   561	    description: Deploy to staging
   562	    program:
   563	      command: ["./scripts/deploy.sh", "{meta.deploy_env}"]
   564	      working_directory: ./infra
   565	    program_timeout: 20m
   566	```
   567	
   568	When `program` is set, `rhei run` spawns the command as a subprocess instead of an agent. The program communicates its outcome via exit code, and transitions from program states can declare `exit_code` conditions for automatic routing:
   569	
   570	```yaml
   571	transitions:
   572	  - from: build
   573	    to: test
   574	    exit_code: 0
   575	  - from: build
   576	    to: failed
   577	    exit_code: nonzero
   578	```
   579	
   580	A state must not declare both `agent` and `program` — they are mutually exclusive. The `program` field is also incompatible with `gating: true` (programs run autonomously).
   581	
   582	See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) for the complete specification including program declaration forms, exit-code transitions, environment variables, timeout handling, and validation rules.
   583	
   584	## MCP Servers and Skills
   585	
   586	States can attach **MCP servers** and **skills** to the agent subprocess. MCP
   587	servers expose tools through the Model Context Protocol; skills bundle
   588	agent-side prompts and resources. Both are tooling that shapes what an agent
   589	can do in a given phase — research, implementation, review, and so on.
   590	
   591	The `mcp_servers` and `skills` fields are lists. Each entry is either a
   592	**registry id** (a string naming an entry in the merged
   593	[`mcp_servers`](rhei-agents.spec.md#mcp_servers) or
   594	[`skills`](rhei-agents.spec.md#skills) settings registry) or an **inline
   595	object** for one-offs that shouldn't pollute global settings.
   596	
   597	### Entry forms
   598	
   599	```yaml
   600	states:
   601	  pending:
   602	    agent: claude-code
   603	    mcp_servers: [postgres]                         # registry id
   604	    skills: [test-authoring]
   605	
   606	  agent-review:
   607	    agent: codex
   608	    mcp_servers:
   609	      - id: postgres                                # registry id (long form)
   610	      - id: grafana
   611	        optional: true                              # warn-and-continue if missing
   612	    skills:
   613	      - id: security-review
   614	      - id: ad-hoc-review                           # inline (no registry entry required)
   615	        path: ./.rhei/skills/ad-hoc-review
   616	        optional: true
   617	```
   618	
   619	The object form accepts `id`, `optional`, and the fields of the corresponding
   620	registry entry (`command`/`url`/`transport`/`env`/... for MCP servers; `path`
   621	and `description` for skills). The string form is shorthand for `{id: <name>}`
   622	with `optional: false`.
   623	
   624	### Effective set
   625	
   626	The **effective set** for a state is `defaults.<kind>` ∪ `state.<kind>`,
   627	deduplicated by id. State-level entries override identically-ided defaults.
   628	Passing `mcp_servers: []` or `skills: []` on a state clears the inherited
   629	`defaults` tooling for that state — leaving the field out inherits the
   630	defaults unchanged. See
   631	[Agents Specification — Resolution Order](rhei-agents.spec.md#resolution-order)
   632	for the full algorithm.
   633	
   634	### Runtime semantics
   635	
   636	- Entries are resolved and availability-checked by `rhei run` at agent spawn
   637	  time — not at `rhei next`.
   638	- Required entries (the default) that fail their availability check block the
   639	  agent spawn. The engine fires an `mcp_unavailable` or `skill_unavailable`
   640	  transition if one is declared from the current state; otherwise the task
   641	  stays in place with an error logged.
   642	- Optional entries (`optional: true`) that fail produce a warning and are
   643	  dropped from the effective set. The agent still spawns with the remaining
   644	  resolved tooling.
   645	- For every declared entry — required or optional — the engine exposes:
   646	  - `{mcp.<name>.available}` / `{skill.<id>.available}` template variables
   647	    resolved to `true` or `false`.
   648	  - `RHEI_MCP_<NAME>_AVAILABLE` / `RHEI_SKILL_<ID>_AVAILABLE` environment
   649	    variables (name uppercased, hyphens and spaces replaced with underscores).
   650	- The aggregate resolved set is also exposed via `RHEI_MCP_SERVERS` and
   651	  `RHEI_SKILLS` as comma-separated id lists containing only the entries that
   652	  started successfully.
   653	
   654	See [Agents Specification — Missing Tooling](rhei-agents.spec.md#missing-tooling)
   655	for availability semantics, timeout behavior, and the
   656	`mcp_unavailable` / `skill_unavailable` transition contract. See
   657	[Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) for declaring those
   658	transitions.
   659	
   660	### Example
   661	
   662	```yaml
   663	states:
   664	  draft:
   665	    description: Research phase — agent needs read access to the issue tracker.
   666	    agent: claude-code
   667	    mcp_servers: [linear]
   668	    instructions: |
   669	      Read Task {task_id}: {task_title} and linked Linear tickets.
   670	
   671	      {if mcp.linear.available}
   672	      Use the Linear MCP to fetch related tickets and comments before writing
   673	      the task description.
   674	      {else}
   675	      Linear is unavailable — rely on the task body only and flag any missing
   676	      context in your description.
   677	      {endif}
   678	
   679	      Transition to `pending` once the description is finalized.
   680	
   681	  pending:
   682	    description: Implementation phase.
   683	    agent: claude-code
   684	    mcp_servers: [postgres]
   685	    skills: [test-authoring]
   686	
   687	  agent-review:
   688	    description: Independent review.
   689	    agent: codex
   690	    mcp_servers:
   691	      - id: postgres
   692	      - id: grafana
   693	        optional: true
   694	    skills: [security-review]
   695	    instructions: |
   696	      Review Task {task_id}.
   697	
   698	      {if mcp.grafana.available}
   699	      Pull relevant latency panels from Grafana for any request-path changes
   700	      and cite them in your findings.
   701	      {else}
   702	      Grafana is unavailable — note the omission in findings but do not block
   703	      the review on it.
   704	      {endif}
   705	```
   706	
   707	## Profiles
   708	
   709	A **profile** is a named bundle of `{initial, allowed}` that defines a
   710	per-node state policy. Profiles are defined once at the top level of the
   711	state machine YAML and referenced from `node_policy`.
   712	
   713	Separating policy from state definitions means:
   714	
   715	- One canonical definition of each state and transition.
   716	- Multiple node kinds can share a profile without duplicating `allowed`
   717	  arrays.
   718	- The root node can use a different profile than task or bug nodes, without
   719	  cloning the state graph.
   720	- `rhei reset` resets each node to its resolved profile's `initial` — there is
   721	  no single machine-wide initial state.
   722	
   723	> The `profiles` block in this spec is distinct from the `models` list of
   724	> *model profiles*. A `models` entry names a model profile identifier
   725	> resolved through settings to a provider/model combination. A `profiles`
   726	> entry is a state policy assigned to nodes. They live at different layers
   727	> of the machine and never resolve against each other.
   728	
   729	### Shape
   730	
   731	```yaml
   732	profiles:
   733	  <profile-name>:
   734	    initial: <state-name>        # starting state for any node using this profile
   735	    allowed: [<state-name>, ...] # states any such node may ever hold
   736	```
   737	
   738	### Per-profile validation
   739	
   740	- `initial` must be defined in `states`.
   741	- Every entry in `allowed` must be defined in `states`.
   742	- `initial` must appear in `allowed`.
   743	- `allowed` must contain at least one state marked `final: true`.
   744	- Every non-final state in `allowed` must have a path — using only
   745	  transitions whose `to` is also in `allowed` — to some final state in
   746	  `allowed`. This reachability check prevents a narrowed `allowed` set from
   747	  silently producing a policy where a node can enter a state it can never
   748	  leave.
   749	
   750	### Example
   751	
   752	```yaml
   753	profiles:
   754	  simple:
   755	    initial: pending
   756	    allowed: [pending, completed, cancelled]
   757	
   758	  reviewed:
   759	    initial: draft
   760	    allowed: [draft, pending, agent-review, agent-review-fix, human-review, completed, cancelled]

 succeeded in 767ms:
   361	Automatic transitions based on conditions, timers, or events configured in the state machine:
   362	
   363	```yaml
   364	transitions:
   365	  - from: retrying
   366	    to: manual-intervention
   367	    condition: retryCount >= 3  # System evaluates this automatically
   368	
   369	  - from: pending
   370	    to: expired
   371	    timeout: 24h  # System triggers after timeout
   372	```
   373	
   374	### 4. Engine Trigger (`triggeredBy: 'engine'`)
   375	
   376	When using `rhei.run()` or similar autonomous execution modes, the Rhei engine advances the workflow by triggering transitions on tasks whose dependencies are satisfied:
   377	
   378	```typescript
   379	// Engine-driven execution
   380	const rhei = new Rhei({ rheiPath: './my-rhei.rhei.md' });
   381	await rhei.run();  // Engine triggers transitions as tasks become ready
   382	```
   383	
   384	This is distinct from `system` triggers (which are condition/timer-based) and `user` triggers (which are explicit API calls). Engine triggers represent the normal workflow progression during autonomous execution.
   385	
   386	### 5. Program Exit-Code Trigger (`triggeredBy: 'system'`)
   387	
   388	When a program state's subprocess exits and has not already advanced the task (via `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`), the engine evaluates exit-code transitions:
   389	
   390	1. Collect all transitions from the current state that declare an `exit_code` field.
   391	2. Match the actual exit code against specific integers and arrays first.
   392	3. If no specific match and exit code is non-zero, try `"nonzero"` transitions.
   393	4. If multiple transitions match, evaluate `condition` fields to disambiguate.
   394	5. The matching transition fires with `triggeredBy: 'system'`.
   395	6. The transition's `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks execute normally.
   396	
   397	```yaml
   398	states:
   399	  build:
   400	    program: "make build"
   401	    program_timeout: 10m
   402	
   403	  test:
   404	    description: Run tests
   405	    program: "make test"
   406	
   407	transitions:
   408	  - from: build
   409	    to: test
   410	    description: Build succeeded
   411	    exit_code: 0
   412	
   413	  - from: build
   414	    to: failed
   415	    description: Build failed
   416	    exit_code: nonzero
   417	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh notify-build-failure"
   418	```
   419	
   420	The `exit_code` field on the transition is only meaningful for program states. Declaring `exit_code` on a transition from a non-program state is a validation error. See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) for the complete exit-code evaluation algorithm and validation rules.
   421	
   422	### 6. Agent Timeout Trigger (`triggeredBy: 'system'`)
   423	
   424	When `rhei run` spawns an agent for a state that declares `agent_timeout`, the engine monitors the agent process duration. If the agent exceeds the timeout:
   425	
   426	1. The engine sends `SIGTERM` to the agent, then `SIGKILL` after a 10-second grace period.
   427	2. The engine evaluates transitions from the current state that have a `timeout` field.
   428	3. If a matching timeout transition exists, it fires with `triggeredBy: 'system'`.
   429	4. The transition's `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks execute normally.
   430	5. If no timeout transition exists, the task remains in its current state and a warning is logged.
   431	
   432	```yaml
   433	states:
   434	  pending:
   435	    agent: claude-code
   436	    agent_timeout: 30m
   437	
   438	  timed-out:
   439	    gating: true
   440	    description: Agent exceeded time budget. Human must decide next step.
   441	
   442	transitions:
   443	  - from: pending
   444	    to: timed-out
   445	    description: Agent exceeded the time budget
   446	    timeout: 30m
   447	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh notify-timeout"
   448	
   449	  - from: timed-out
   450	    to: pending
   451	    description: Human decided to retry after timeout
   452	
   453	  - from: timed-out
   454	    to: cancelled
   455	    description: Human decided to abandon after timeout
   456	```
   457	
   458	The `timeout` field on the transition serves dual purpose: it marks the transition as a timeout handler for `rhei run` agent mode, and it can be used by other runtimes for time-based system triggers. The `transitionData` for timeout-triggered transitions includes `{ "timeout": "<duration>", "agent": "<agent-id>" }`.
   459	
   460	See [Agents Specification — Timeout Handling](rhei-agents.spec.md#timeout-handling) for the full timeout configuration and behavior.
   461	
   462	### 7. Tooling-Unavailable Trigger (`triggeredBy: 'system'`)
   463	
   464	When `rhei run` is about to spawn an agent for a state that declares required
   465	MCP servers or skills (`optional: false`, the default), the engine first
   466	checks availability. If any required entry fails its availability check:
   467	
   468	1. The engine does not spawn the agent.
   469	2. It collects the ids of the failed required entries.
   470	3. It evaluates transitions from the current state whose `mcp_unavailable`
   471	   or `skill_unavailable` field matches. `true` matches any failure of that
   472	   kind; an explicit id list matches only when one of the listed ids failed.
   473	4. If a matching transition exists, it fires with `triggeredBy: 'system'`.
   474	5. The transition's `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks execute normally.
   475	6. If no matching transition exists, the task remains in its current state
   476	   and `rhei run` logs an error listing the unavailable ids.
   477	
   478	```yaml
   479	states:
   480	  agent-review:
   481	    description: Independent review with required tooling.
   482	    agent: codex
   483	    mcp_servers:
   484	      - id: postgres
   485	      - id: grafana
   486	        optional: true
   487	
   488	  tooling-missing:
   489	    gating: true
   490	    description: Required tooling is unavailable. Human must decide next step.
   491	
   492	transitions:
   493	  - from: agent-review
   494	    to: tooling-missing
   495	    description: A required MCP server was unavailable
   496	    mcp_unavailable: true
   497	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh notify-tooling-missing"
   498	
   499	  - from: tooling-missing
   500	    to: agent-review
   501	    description: Human confirmed tooling is back, retry review
   502	
   503	  - from: tooling-missing
   504	    to: cancelled
   505	    description: Human abandoned after persistent tooling failure
   506	```
   507	
   508	A transition may also target specific ids:
   509	
   510	```yaml
   511	transitions:
   512	  - from: deploy
   513	    to: blocked-on-cloud
   514	    description: Cloud MCP specifically is unavailable
   515	    mcp_unavailable: [cloud-provider]
   516	```
   517	
   518	The `transitionData` for tooling-triggered transitions includes
   519	`{ "unavailable": ["<id>", ...], "kind": "mcp" | "skill" }`. Optional
   520	(`optional: true`) entries never trigger these transitions — they are dropped
   521	with a warning regardless.
   522	
   523	See [Agents Specification — Missing Tooling](rhei-agents.spec.md#missing-tooling)
   524	for availability semantics and
   525	[States Specification — MCP Servers and Skills](rhei-states.spec.md#mcp-servers-and-skills)
   526	for the per-state `mcp_servers` and `skills` fields.
   527	
   528	---
   529	
   530	## YAML State Machine Format Specification
   531	
   532	This section defines the formal structure of YAML state machine configuration files. All state machines must conform to this specification.
   533	
   534	### Root-Level Fields
   535	
   536	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   537	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   538	| `name` | string | Yes | Unique identifier for the state machine |
   539	| `models` | string array | No | Declared model profile identifiers available to states in this machine |
   540	| `version` | string | Yes | Semantic version of the state machine definition |
   541	| `states` | object | Yes | Map of state names to state definitions |
   542	| `transitions` | array | Yes | List of allowed state transitions |
   543	| `callbacks` | object | No | Platform-specific callback mappings |
   544	| `error_handling` | object | No | Error handling and recovery configuration |
   545	
   546	### State Definition
   547	
   548	Each state is defined as a key-value pair in the `states` object:
   549	
   550	```yaml
   551	states:
   552	  <state-name>:
   553	    description: <string>       # Required: Human-readable description of the state
   554	    instructions: <string>      # Optional: Agent-facing instructions for work in this state
   555	    final: <boolean>            # Optional: true if this is a terminal state (no outgoing transitions)
   556	    gating: <boolean>           # Optional: true if no autonomous (agent/engine) transitions are allowed out
   557	    visits: <integer>           # Optional: maximum number of visits permitted for this state
   558	    target: <string>            # Optional: inline execution target selector
   559	    all_targets: [<string>]     # Optional: run this state once per listed target
   560	    all_models: [<string>]      # Optional: list of declared model profiles; run this state once per listed model
   561	    model: <string>             # Optional: one declared model profile allowed for this state
   562	    agent: <string>             # Optional: coding agent id for this state (see Agents Specification)
   563	    agent_mode: <string>        # Optional: named mode on the resolved agent
   564	    agent_timeout: <duration>   # Optional: max time an agent may work in this state (e.g., "30m")
   565	    program: <string|object>    # Optional: deterministic program to execute (see Program States Specification)
   566	    program_timeout: <duration> # Optional: max time a program may run in this state (e.g., "10m")
   567	    mcp_servers: [<string|object>]  # Optional: MCP servers attached to the agent for this state
   568	    skills: [<string|object>]       # Optional: agent skills enabled for this state
   569	```
   570	
   571	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   572	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   573	| `description` | string | Yes | Human-readable explanation of what this state represents |
   574	| `instructions` | string | No | Agent-facing guidance for work in this state. Supports [template variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality) resolved by `rhei next` at output time. |
   575	| `personality` | string | No | Optional role framing printed alongside the next claimed task when this state is active. Supports [template variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality). |
   576	| `final` | boolean | No | Marks this as a terminal state. Tasks in final states cannot transition further |
   577	| `gating` | boolean | No | Marks this as a gating state. When `true`, autonomous commands (`rhei next`, `rhei complete`, engine-triggered transitions) must not transition out of this state. Only explicit human-initiated transitions (`rhei transition` with `triggeredBy: 'user'`) are allowed. |
   578	| `visits` | integer | No | Maximum number of visits permitted for this state before the loop budget is exhausted |
   579	| `target` | string | No | Inline execution target selector. Preferred over the legacy `model` + `agent` split for new workflows. |
   580	| `all_targets` | string array | No | Explicit list of execution target selectors; the state runs once for each listed target. Preferred over `all_models` for new fanout workflows. |
   581	| `all_models` | string array | No | Explicit list of declared model profile identifiers; the state runs once for each listed model |
   582	| `model` | string | No | Restricts the state to one model profile declared in the machine-level `models` list |
   583	| `agent` | string | No | Coding agent id for this state. Must resolve against the merged `agents` registry (built-ins + `settings.json`). Inline agent objects are not accepted — declare custom agents in `agents.<id>` first. See [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md). |
   584	| `agent_mode` | string | No | Named flag set from the resolved agent's `modes` map (e.g., `yolo`, `safe`). See [Agents Specification — Modes](rhei-agents.spec.md#modes). |
   585	| `agent_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time an agent may work in this state (e.g., `30m`, `1h`). When exceeded, `rhei run` kills the agent and fires a timeout transition if one is declared. |
   586	| `program` | string or object | No | Deterministic program command for this state. String form runs via shell. Object form specifies `command`, `env`, `working_directory`. Mutually exclusive with `agent`. See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md). |
   587	| `program_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time a program may run in this state (e.g., `10m`, `1h`). Same timeout mechanism as `agent_timeout`. |
   588	| `inputs` | artifact array | No | Required file artifacts that must exist before entering or working this state |
   589	| `outputs` | artifact array | No | Required file artifacts that must exist before leaving this state |
   590	| `mcp_servers` | array | No | MCP server entries (ids or inline definitions) attached to the agent subprocess. Individual entries may be marked `optional: true`. Mutually exclusive with `gating: true` and `program:`. See [States Specification — MCP Servers and Skills](rhei-states.spec.md#mcp-servers-and-skills). |
   591	| `skills` | array | No | Skill entries enabled for the agent in this state. Same shape and exclusions as `mcp_servers`. |
   592	
   593	Model selection rules:
   594	- The machine-level `models` list is optional. When omitted, states are not model-constrained.
   595	- A state may set `target: <selector>` or `all_targets: [<selector>, ...]` as
   596	  an inline execution selector.
   597	- `target` and `all_targets` are mutually exclusive.
   598	- `target` / `all_targets` must not be combined with `model`, `all_models`,
   599	  `agent`, or `agent_mode`.
   600	- Target selectors must use one of these forms:
   601	  `<agent>:<model>`, `<agent>[<mode>]:<model>`,
   602	  `<agent>:<provider>:<model>`, or
   603	  `<agent>[<mode>]:<provider>:<model>`.
   604	- `all_targets`, when present, must be a non-empty list of unique selectors.
   605	- In a target selector, `<agent>` must resolve against the merged `agents`
   606	  registry.
   607	- In a target selector, `<mode>`, when present, must resolve against the
   608	  selected agent's declared modes.
   609	- In a target selector, `<provider>`, when present, must be non-empty.
   610	- In a target selector, `<model>` must be non-empty.
   611	- A state may set `all_models: [<name>, ...]` or `model: <name>`, but not both.
   612	- `model` must reference a value declared in the machine-level `models` list.
   613	- `all_models`, when present, must be a non-empty list of unique values declared in the machine-level `models` list.
   614	- A state with `all_models` is executed once per listed model.
   615	- A state with `all_targets` is executed once per listed target.
   616	- `visits` may be combined with either `all_models` or `model`.
   617	- `visits` may also be combined with either `all_targets` or `target`.
   618	- `visits`, when present, must be an integer greater than or equal to `1`.
   619	- `inputs` and `outputs`, when present, must be arrays of unique artifact definitions keyed by `name`.
   620	- Artifact `path` values are execution-root-relative templates; see [main spec — State Artifact Contracts](../rhei.spec.md#10-state-artifact-contracts) for the definition of execution root. After expansion, they must remain within that root.
   621	
   622	Artifact definition:
   623	
   624	```yaml
   625	states:
   626	  review:
   627	    outputs:
   628	      - name: findings
   629	        path: runtime/findings/{task_id}.md
   630	        description: Concrete review findings for the task
   631	```
   632	
   633	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   634	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   635	| `name` | string | Yes | Stable identifier for the artifact within that state |
   636	| `path` | string | Yes | Workspace-relative file path template |
   637	| `description` | string | No | Human-readable explanation of the artifact |
   638	
   639	Supported template variables:
   640	
   641	- `{task_id}` - current task id
   642	- `{state}` - canonical unsuffixed state name
   643	- `{visit_count}` - current visit number for counted-loop states (only available when the state declares `visits`)
   644	- `{target}` - current execution target selector (only available when the state declares `target` or `all_targets`)
   645	- `{target.slug}` - filesystem-safe slug for the current target selector
   646	- `{agent}` - current agent id
   647	- `{agent.mode}` - current agent mode, if any
   648	- `{model}` - current model identifier (available when the state declares `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`)
   649	- `{model.provider}` - current model provider id
   650	- `{model.name}` - current provider model name
   651	
   652	### Counted Loops
   653	
   654	This section describes the runtime semantics of the `visits` field, also
   655	called *counted visits* in the main plan specification and the states
   656	specification. The three terms — `visits`, *counted visits*, and *counted
   657	loops* — refer to the same mechanism.
   658	
   659	`visits` is a state-level loop budget. It is used when a workflow intentionally cycles through the same state multiple times before taking a non-loop exit.
   660	
   661	Rules:
   662	
   663	- `visits` applies to every entry into that state, including the initial entry and later loop-back re-entries.
   664	- Starting in a counted state records `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<state-name> = 1`.
   665	- Each later loop-back re-entry increments `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<state-name>` by `1`.
   666	- The task's active `**State:**` value mirrors that count by writing `<state>-<n>` for visits greater than `1`; visit `1` stays as the bare state name.
   667	- When evaluating transitions from a counted-loop state, runtimes should expose:
   668	  - `visitCount`: the current value of `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<state-name>`
   669	  - `visits`: the configured state-level loop budget
   670	- Once `visitCount >= visits`, further loop-back transitions into that state are exhausted and the machine must take another allowed transition such as escalation, human review, or completion.
   671	- When a state also declares `all_models`, visit accounting is scoped to each model-specific execution of that state.
   672	- When a state also declares `all_targets`, visit accounting is scoped to each target-specific execution of that state.
   673	- On a state that declares [`poll:`](rhei-states.spec.md#polling-states), the same `stateVisits` entry records poll attempts. Transitions from that state may use `pollAttempts` (alias for `visitCount`) and `pollMaxAttempts` (alias for `poll.max_attempts`) for clarity; both names are only defined on transitions whose `from` state declares `poll:`. A self-loop transition from a poll state is interpreted by `rhei run` as "retry after `poll.interval`" and releases the `--parallel` slot between attempts; once `pollAttempts >= pollMaxAttempts`, the engine refuses self-loops and picks the first matching non-self-loop transition instead.
   674	
   675	Example:
   676	
   677	```yaml
   678	states:
   679	  agent-review:
   680	    description: Review the implementation
   681	    instructions: |
   682	      Review the implementation. If changes are needed and loop budget remains,
   683	      transition to `agent-review-fix`. If the loop budget is exhausted,
   684	      transition to `human-review`.
   685	    visits: 3
   686	
   687	  agent-review-fix:
   688	    description: Apply reviewer findings
   689	    instructions: |
   690	      Address reviewer findings only, then transition back to `agent-review`.
   691	
   692	  human-review:
   693	    description: Human escalation after repeated review/fix cycles
   694	
   695	transitions:
   696	  - from: pending
   697	    to: agent-review
   698	    description: Submit implementation for review
   699	
   700	  - from: agent-review
   701	    to: agent-review-fix
   702	    description: Review requested changes while loop budget remains
   703	    condition: visitCount < visits
   704	
   705	  - from: agent-review
   706	    to: human-review
   707	    description: Escalate after the counted review/fix loop is exhausted
   708	    condition: visitCount >= visits
   709	
   710	  - from: agent-review-fix
   711	    to: agent-review
   712	    description: Re-submit after fixes; increments the `agent-review` visit counter to the next visit
   713	```
   714	
   715	### Transition Definition
   716	
   717	Each transition in the `transitions` array specifies an allowed state change:
   718	
   719	```yaml
   720	transitions:
   721	  - from: <state-name|"*">  # Required: Source state or wildcard
   722	    to: <state-name>        # Required: Target state
   723	    description: <string>   # Required: Explanation of when/why this transition occurs
   724	    on_leave: <callback>    # Optional: Callback invoked when leaving the source state
   725	    on_enter: <callback>    # Optional: Callback invoked when entering the target state
   726	    condition: <expression> # Optional: Condition that must be true for system-triggered transitions
   727	    timeout: <duration>     # Optional: Duration after which system triggers this transition
   728	    exit_code: <int|array|"nonzero">  # Optional: Exit-code condition for program state transitions
   729	    mcp_unavailable: <bool|[<id>, ...]>    # Optional: Fires when a required MCP server is unavailable
   730	    skill_unavailable: <bool|[<id>, ...]>  # Optional: Fires when a required skill is unavailable
   731	    max_retries: <integer>  # Optional: Maximum retry attempts for this transition
   732	    retry_delay: <duration> # Optional: Delay between retry attempts
   733	```
   734	
   735	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   736	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   737	| `from` | string | Yes | Source state name, or `"*"` for wildcard (matches any non-final state) |
   738	| `to` | string | Yes | Target state name |
   739	| `description` | string | Yes | Human-readable explanation of the transition's purpose and when it occurs |
   740	| `on_leave` | string | No | Callback function identifier invoked before leaving the source state |
   741	| `on_enter` | string | No | Callback function identifier invoked after entering the target state |
   742	| `condition` | string | No | Expression evaluated for system-triggered transitions |
   743	| `timeout` | string | No | Duration (e.g., `24h`, `30m`) after which system triggers this transition |
   744	| `exit_code` | integer, integer array, or `"nonzero"` | No | Exit-code condition for transitions from program states. Only evaluated when a program exits without calling `rhei transition`. See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md#exit-code-transitions). |
   745	| `mcp_unavailable` | boolean or string array | No | When `true`, fires when any required MCP server on the source state fails its availability check. When an array, fires only when one of the listed ids failed. Only valid on transitions from agent states. See [Tooling-Unavailable Trigger](#7-tooling-unavailable-trigger-triggeredby-system). |
   746	| `skill_unavailable` | boolean or string array | No | Same shape as `mcp_unavailable`, for skills. |
   747	| `max_retries` | integer | No | Maximum automatic retry attempts |
   748	| `retry_delay` | string | No | Delay between retries (e.g., `30s`, `5m`) |
   749	
   750	### Artifact Enforcement
   751	
   752	State artifact contracts (see [States Specification — Artifact Contracts](rhei-states.spec.md#artifact-contracts) for the schema) are enforced around transitions:
   753	
   754	1. Before entering a target state, the runtime resolves `target.inputs` and
   755	   rejects the transition if any required input file does not exist.
   756	2. After `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks complete, but before the state write
   757	   is committed, the runtime resolves `source.outputs` and rejects the
   758	   transition if any required output file does not exist.
   759	3. `rhei complete` is subject to the same output checks as `rhei transition`.
   760	4. In v1, enforcement is file-existence only. Content validation is out of

