   707	## Profiles
   708	
   709	A **profile** is a named bundle of `{initial, allowed}` that defines a
   710	per-node state policy. Profiles are defined once at the top level of the
   711	state machine YAML and referenced from `node_policy`.
   712	
   713	Separating policy from state definitions means:
   714	
   715	- One canonical definition of each state and transition.
   716	- Multiple node kinds can share a profile without duplicating `allowed`
   717	  arrays.
   718	- The root node can use a different profile than task or bug nodes, without
   719	  cloning the state graph.
   720	- `rhei reset` resets each node to its resolved profile's `initial` — there is
   721	  no single machine-wide initial state.
   722	
   723	> The `profiles` block in this spec is distinct from the `models` list of
   724	> *model profiles*. A `models` entry names a model profile identifier
   725	> resolved through settings to a provider/model combination. A `profiles`
   726	> entry is a state policy assigned to nodes. They live at different layers
   727	> of the machine and never resolve against each other.
   728	
   729	### Shape
   730	
   731	```yaml
   732	profiles:
   733	  <profile-name>:
   734	    initial: <state-name>        # starting state for any node using this profile
   735	    allowed: [<state-name>, ...] # states any such node may ever hold
   736	```
   737	
   738	### Per-profile validation
   739	
   740	- `initial` must be defined in `states`.
   741	- Every entry in `allowed` must be defined in `states`.
   742	- `initial` must appear in `allowed`.
   743	- `allowed` must contain at least one state marked `final: true`.
   744	- Every non-final state in `allowed` must have a path — using only
   745	  transitions whose `to` is also in `allowed` — to some final state in
   746	  `allowed`. This reachability check prevents a narrowed `allowed` set from
   747	  silently producing a policy where a node can enter a state it can never
   748	  leave.
   749	
   750	### Example
   751	
   752	```yaml
   753	profiles:
   754	  simple:
   755	    initial: pending
   756	    allowed: [pending, completed, cancelled]
   757	
   758	  reviewed:
   759	    initial: draft
   760	    allowed: [draft, pending, agent-review, agent-review-fix, human-review, completed, cancelled]
   761	
   762	  light-review:
   763	    initial: pending
   764	    allowed: [pending, agent-review, completed, cancelled]
   765	```
   766	
   767	`allowed` is always a wholesale set — profiles are referenced by name, never
   768	merged. Two profiles that share most of their states still list each state
   769	explicitly.
   770	
   771	## Node Policy
   772	
   773	`node_policy` maps each node in a plan to a profile. It has four keys: the
   774	required `root` and `default`, and the optional `by_type` and `overrides`.
   775	
   776	### Shape
   777	
   778	```yaml
   779	node_policy:
   780	  root: <profile-name>           # required: profile the (always-rhei) root runs
   781	  default: <profile-name>        # required: fallback for any non-root kind not listed
   782	  by_type:                       # optional: per-kind overrides
   783	    <kind>: <profile-name>
   784	  overrides:                     # optional: ordered list for multi-dimensional cases
   785	    - match: { type: <kind>, level: <n> }
   786	      profile: <profile-name>
   787	```
   788	
   789	### Resolution
   790	
   791	For a given node, resolve its profile in this order:
   792	
   793	1. If the node is the root (level 0, kind `rhei`), use `node_policy.root`.
   794	2. Otherwise, walk `node_policy.overrides` in declaration order. Use the
   795	   profile of the first entry whose `match` matches the node. A `match`
   796	   block may include `type` and/or `level`; every specified field must
   797	   match the node.
   798	3. Otherwise, if `node_policy.by_type[<kind>]` is defined for the node's
   799	   kind, use it.
   800	4. Otherwise, use `node_policy.default`.
   801	
   802	The resolved profile's `initial` is the node's starting state; its `allowed`
   803	set is the authoritative list of states that node may ever hold. `rhei reset`
   804	returns each node to its resolved profile's `initial`.
   805	
   806	### Validation
   807	
   808	- `node_policy.root` is required; it must reference a profile defined in
   809	  `profiles`.
   810	- `node_policy.default` is required; it must reference a profile defined in
   811	  `profiles`.
   812	- Every key of `node_policy.by_type` must appear in `structure.nodeKinds`.
   813	  The reserved name `rhei` must not appear as a `by_type` key — the root is
   814	  configured through `node_policy.root`, not here.
   815	- Every profile reference in `by_type` and `overrides[].profile` must
   816	  resolve to a profile defined in `profiles`.
   817	- `overrides[].match` keys are limited to `type` and `level`. `type` values
   818	  must be in `structure.nodeKinds`. `level` values must be integers in
   819	  `[1, structure.maxLevels]`. The root is not matchable through `overrides`;
   820	  use `node_policy.root`.
   821	- Each profile referenced by `node_policy` must pass the per-profile
   822	  validation rules above.
   823	- Any authored `**State:**` on a node must appear in that node's resolved
   824	  profile's `allowed` set.
   825	
   826	### Example
   827	
   828	```yaml
   829	node_policy:
   830	  root: reviewed        # the root runs through the full review flow
   831	  default: simple       # nodes without a type-specific mapping use this
   832	  by_type:
   833	    task: reviewed
   834	    bug:  light-review
   835	  overrides:
   836	    - match: { type: task, level: 3 }   # leaf-level tasks skip review
   837	      profile: simple
   838	```
   839	
   840	In this configuration, a level-3 `task` uses `simple` (via `overrides`), a
   841	level-2 `task` uses `reviewed` (via `by_type`), a `bug` at any level uses
   842	`light-review`, and a `story` — a declared kind without a `by_type` entry —
   843	uses `simple`.
   844	
   845	## States
   846	
   847	| State | Description | Final | Gating |
   848	|-------|-------------|-------|--------|
   849	| `draft` | Task is still being shaped; description not ready for execution | No | No |
   850	| `pending` | Task ready for implementation once prerequisites are `completed` | No | No |
   851	| `agent-review` | A separate reviewing agent inspects the result | No | No |
   852	| `agent-review-fix` | Implementing agent applies reviewer findings, no scope change | No | No |
   853	| `human-review` | Work paused pending human inspection; no autonomous exit | No | Yes |
   854	| `completed` | Task finished successfully; immutable | Yes | No |
   855	| `cancelled` | Task no longer needed; skip entirely | Yes | No |
   856	
   857	Whether a state is a node's starting state is determined by the node's
   858	resolved profile (see [Profiles](#profiles) and [Node Policy](#node-policy)),
   859	not by a per-state flag.
   860	
   861	## Transitions
   862	
   863	See [states.yaml](states.yaml) for the enforced transition table. Summary:
   864	
   865	- `draft` → `pending` | `cancelled`
   866	- `pending` → `agent-review` | `human-review` | `completed` | `cancelled`
   867	- `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix` (fail) | `human-review` (pass, gated) | `completed` (pass, ungated)
   868	- `agent-review-fix` → `agent-review` | `cancelled`
   869	- `human-review` → `pending` | `completed` | `cancelled`
   870	
   871	Any transition not listed in `states.yaml` is forbidden.
   872	
   873	### Completion paths
   874	
   875	Not every state can be completed directly via `rhei complete`. The command requires a non-cancelled terminal state reachable in one hop:
   876	
   877	- From `pending`, `agent-review`: direct completion to `completed` is available.
   878	- From `agent-review-fix`: no direct path to `completed` exists. The agent must transition to `agent-review` first, then complete from there.
   879	- From `human-review`: completion is blocked because the state is gating (`gating: true`). Only a human-initiated `rhei transition` can exit this state.
