     1	# Rhei State Machine Writer
     2	
     3	This document specifies a new role in the Rhei ecosystem: the **State Machine Writer**. It designs custom state machines (YAML files) tailored to a project's specification, team structure, and workflow requirements.
     4	
     5	For the YAML schema and transition callback system see the [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md). For the default state machine see the [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md).
     6	
     7	## Purpose
     8	
     9	The default `rhei` state machine covers a generic agent workflow (draft, pending, review, completed, with optional human review). Many projects need domain-specific workflows:
    10	
    11	- A compliance-heavy project may require multiple approval gates from distinct teams.
    12	- A data pipeline project may model stages like `ingesting`, `transforming`, `validating`, `published`.
    13	- A release process may need `staging`, `canary`, `rollout`, `stable`.
    14	
    15	The state machine writer analyzes two inputs — the **project specification** and the **project teams** — and produces a state machine YAML file that encodes the project's real workflow as Rhei states and transitions.
    16	
    17	## Inputs
    18	
    19	### 1. Project Specification
    20	
    21	The project specification describes what the project does, its deliverables, phases, quality gates, and constraints. This can come from:
    22	
    23	- A requirements document, PRD, or design doc.
    24	- A README or AGENTS.md in the repository.
    25	- Verbal description from the user.
    26	- An existing Rhei plan whose workflow doesn't match the default machine.
    27	
    28	The state machine writer extracts from the specification:
    29	
    30	| Extract | Maps to |
    31	|---------|---------|
    32	| Distinct workflow phases | States |
    33	| Phase ordering and branching | Transitions |
    34	| Quality gates and checkpoints | Gating states (no autonomous exit) |
    35	| Failure modes and recovery paths | Error/retry states and transitions |
    36	| Automated checks | Callback-eligible transitions |
    37	
    38	### 2. Project Teams
    39	
    40	The team structure describes who is involved and what authority each team or role has. This can come from:
    41	
    42	- An explicit team list with roles.
    43	- Organizational context described by the user.
    44	- Existing approval workflows (PR reviewers, sign-off chains).
    45	
    46	The state machine writer maps teams to workflow elements:
    47	
    48	| Team aspect | Maps to |
    49	|-------------|---------|
    50	| Teams that must approve before proceeding | Gating states with team name (e.g., `security-review`, `legal-review`) |
    51	| Teams that perform work | Work states with team-specific instructions |
    52	| Handoff points between teams | Transitions between team-owned states |
    53	| Autonomous agents | Non-gating states with agent instructions |
    54	| Human decision-makers | Gating states (no autonomous exit) |
    55	
    56	## Output
    57	
    58	The state machine writer produces a single YAML file conforming to the [YAML State Machine Format](rhei-transitions.spec.md#yaml-state-machine-format-specification). The file is ready to be referenced by a Rhei plan's `**States:**` declaration.
    59	
    60	### Output Structure
    61	
    62	```yaml
    63	name: <project-derived-name>
    64	version: 1.0
    65	personality: <optional agent persona or role framing text>
    66	models:                              # optional: declare model profile identifiers
    67	  - <model-id>
    68	  - <model-id>
    69	
    70	states:
    71	  <state-name>:
    72	    description: <what this state means in the project context>     # required
    73	    instructions: |                                                 # optional
    74	      <agent-facing guidance: what to do in this state, when to transition out>
    75	    personality: <optional state-specific role framing override>
    76	    final: true|false    # at least one state must be final
    77	    gating: true|false   # optional: if true, no autonomous exit allowed
    78	    visits: <integer>    # optional: max counted visits for loop states
    79	    all_models: [<model-id>, ...] # optional: run once for each listed declared model profile
    80	    model: <model-id>      # optional: exactly one declared model profile may work this state
    81	
    82	transitions:
    83	  - from: <source-state>
    84	    to: <target-state>
    85	    description: <when and why this transition occurs>              # required
    86	    # Optional callback fields when automation is needed:
    87	    # on_leave: <callback-name>
    88	    # on_enter: <callback-name>
    89	    # condition: <expression>
    90	    # timeout: <duration>
    91	
    92	profiles:                            # required: named state policies
    93	  <profile-name>:
    94	    initial: <state-name>            # starting state for nodes using this profile
    95	    allowed: [<state-name>, ...]     # states any such node may ever hold
    96	
    97	node_policy:                         # required: maps nodes to profiles
    98	  root: <profile-name>               # profile the (always-rhei) root runs
    99	  default: <profile-name>            # fallback for non-root kinds not listed
   100	  by_type:                           # optional: per-kind overrides
   101	    <kind>: <profile-name>
   102	  overrides:                         # optional: ordered, first-match-wins
   103	    - match: { type: <kind>, level: <n> }
   104	      profile: <profile-name>
   105	
   106	# Optional: platform-specific callback mappings
   107	# callbacks:
   108	#   cli:
   109	#     <callback-name>: <implementation-path>
   110	#   nodejs:
   111	#     <callback-name>: <implementation-path>
   112	```
   113	
   114	When a machine declares `models`, each state may either:
   115	
   116	- omit model selectors entirely
   117	- set `all_models: [<model-id>, ...]`
   118	- set `model: <model-id>`
   119	
   120	It must not set both `all_models` and `model` on the same state.
   121	
   122	## Design Rules
   123	
   124	The state machine writer follows these rules when designing a state machine:
   125	
   126	### State Design
   127	
   128	1. **Every distinct workflow phase gets its own state.** Don't overload a single state with multiple meanings. If two phases have different instructions or different exit conditions, they are different states.
   129	
   130	2. **Name states after what is happening, not who is doing it.** Prefer `security-review` over `security-team`. The state describes the phase; the instructions describe the actor.
   131	
   132	3. **Declare starting states on profiles, not on states.** A state definition never carries an `initial: true` flag. Each profile in the top-level `profiles` block declares its own `initial` state; a node resolves to a profile through `node_policy`, and that profile's `initial` is where the node starts. In most workflows, the initial is a "ready" or "pending" state — not an active work state.
   133	
   134	4. **Mark at least one state as `final: true`.** Terminal states are absorbing — no outgoing transitions. Every workflow needs at least a success terminal (`completed`, `deployed`, `published`) and typically a cancellation terminal (`cancelled`, `abandoned`).
   135	
   136	5. **Make human approval gates explicit.** Any state where an agent must stop and wait for human judgment should have instructions that say "do not transition out of this state autonomously." These are gating states. Name them to reflect the approver: `legal-review`, `manager-approval`, `security-sign-off`.
   137	
   138	6. **Keep state count proportional to workflow complexity.** A simple project needs 4-6 states. A complex multi-team pipeline might need 8-12. More than 15 states suggests the workflow should be split into separate state machines for different plan types.
   139	
   140	7. **Include recovery states when failure is expected.** If a phase can fail and be retried, model the retry path explicitly (e.g., `validation-failed` → `fixing` → `validating`). Don't rely on implicit "go back to the previous state."
   141	
   142	### Transition Design
   143	
   144	1. **Every transition must be explicitly declared.** Unlisted transitions are forbidden. This is the core safety property of Rhei state machines.
   145	
   146	2. **Transitions encode the project's real workflow, not hypothetical paths.** If a transition never happens in practice, don't declare it. If a transition is rare but valid, declare it.
   147	
   148	3. **Fan-out from a state represents decisions.** When a state has multiple outgoing transitions, each target represents a different outcome. Document in the transition's `description` when each path is taken.
   149	
   150	4. **The transition graph must be connected.** For every profile, every state in that profile's `allowed` set other than its `initial` must be reachable from the `initial` state using transitions whose `to` also lies in `allowed`. Every non-terminal state in `allowed` must have a path to at least one final state in `allowed`. Unreachable or dead-end states in a profile are design errors.
   151	
   152	5. **Provide a cancellation path.** Use a wildcard transition (`from: "*"`) to a `cancelled` terminal state, or declare explicit cancellation transitions from each non-terminal state. Every task must be cancellable.
   153	
   154	6. **Team handoffs are transitions.** When work passes from one team to another, model it as a transition between team-owned states. The `on_leave` callback on the source state packages the deliverable; the `on_enter` callback on the target state notifies the receiving team.
   155	
   156	### Profile and Node Policy Design
   157	
   158	1. **Start with a single default profile.** If every node kind in the plan follows the same flow, define one profile (for example `default`) whose `allowed` set is the full list of states, and point both `node_policy.root` and `node_policy.default` at it. Only split into multiple profiles once you have concrete evidence that different kinds need different flows — it's easier to split later than to collapse prematurely fractured profiles.
   159	
   160	2. **Name profiles for the policy, not the kind.** Prefer `reviewed`, `simple`, `light-review` over `task-profile`, `bug-profile`. A profile can apply to multiple kinds; naming it after a kind implies a coupling that isn't there.
   161	
   162	3. **Each profile's `allowed` is wholesale.** Profiles are referenced by name, never merged. Two profiles that share most of their states still list each state explicitly. This keeps the meaning of `allowed` predictable and removes any "what wins where" resolution rules.
   163	
   164	4. **The root always resolves through `node_policy.root`.** The root node's kind is always `rhei` (a reserved kind), so it's never matched by `by_type` or `overrides`. Pick its profile explicitly — often it shares a profile with the top-level work kind, but there's no requirement to.
   165	
   166	5. **Use `overrides` only when `by_type` cannot express the rule.** `by_type` covers the common case ("all tasks follow this flow"). Add an `overrides` entry only for genuinely multi-dimensional cases — for example, "leaf-level tasks skip review." Entries are first-match-wins in declaration order; keep the list short enough to read top to bottom.
   167	
   168	### Instructions Design
   169	
   170	1. **Write instructions for the actor in that state.** If the state is for an agent, write what the agent should do. If the state is a human gate, write what the human is expected to decide.
   171	
   172	2. **Encode exit conditions structurally, not in instructions.** Under `orchestrator` authority, `rhei run` derives completion from subprocess exit plus the state's required `outputs:`, and it selects the next state from transition `condition` / `exit_code` fields. `instructions` and `personality` therefore describe the domain work only; they must not tell the actor how or when to stop, or when to call transition commands. Gating states (`gating: true`) are the one exception: no subprocess is spawned there, so their instructions address a human reader and should explicitly say "do not transition out of this state autonomously" to mark the hand-off. See [Agents Specification — Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority).
   173	
   174	3. **Reference concrete artifacts.** Don't write "review the work." Write "review the implementation against the task description and its child task nodes. Check that tests pass and lint is clean."
   175	
   176	4. **Use template variables instead of placeholders.** When instructions reference task-specific data, use resolved template variables (`{task_id}`, `{task_title}`, `{visit_count}`, `{visits}`, `{model}`) instead of prose placeholders like `<id>`. When a state declares artifact contracts (`inputs:` / `outputs:` — see [States Specification — Artifact Contracts](rhei-states.spec.md#artifact-contracts) for the YAML schema), reference them by name (`{input.<name>.path}`, `{output.<name>.path}`) instead of repeating raw paths. See the [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality) for the full variable namespace.
   177	
   178	## Workflow
   179	
   180	The state machine writer follows this process:
   181	
   182	1. **Gather inputs.** Read the project specification and team structure. If either is missing or incomplete, ask the user before proceeding.
   183	
   184	2. **Identify phases.** List the distinct workflow phases from the specification. Each phase becomes a candidate state.
   185	
   186	3. **Identify actors.** Map each phase to its actor: which team or agent type performs work in that phase, and who approves the exit.
   187	
   188	4. **Draft states.** For each phase, write a state with a description and instructions. Mark final states. Do not mark initial states here — initial states belong to profiles (step 6).
   189	
   190	5. **Draft transitions.** For each pair of phases that have a direct handoff, declare a transition. Add a description explaining when the transition fires.
   191	
   192	6. **Draft profiles and node policy.** Identify which node kinds in the plan need distinct flows (often there's only one). For each distinct flow, define a profile with an `initial` and `allowed` set. Point `node_policy.root` and `node_policy.default` at profiles, and add `by_type` entries for any non-root kind whose flow differs from `default`. Add `overrides` only for multi-dimensional rules.
   193	
   194	7. **Add safety paths.** For every profile, ensure every non-final state in `allowed` has a path to a final state in `allowed`, using only transitions whose `to` is also in `allowed`. Add cancellation transitions. Add recovery/retry paths for phases that can fail.
   195	
   196	8. **Add callbacks (optional).** If the project uses programmatic transitions, assign `on_leave` and `on_enter` callback names to transitions that integrate with external systems.
   197	
   198	9. **Validate the design.**
   199	   - Every profile declares an `initial` and a non-empty `allowed` set.
   200	   - Every profile's `initial` is a member of its `allowed` set.
   201	   - Every profile's `allowed` contains at least one final state.
   202	   - `node_policy.root` and `node_policy.default` reference defined profiles.
   203	   - Every `by_type` key is a declared non-root node kind; `rhei` is not used as a `by_type` key.
   204	   - For every profile, every non-final state in `allowed` has a path to a final state in `allowed` using transitions confined to `allowed`.
   205	   - At least one final state exists globally (typically two: success and cancellation).
   206	   - No orphan states (defined in `states` but not referenced by any profile's `allowed`, transition, or override).
   207	   - State names are lowercase, hyphenated identifiers (matching the `IDENTIFIER` grammar production).
   208	   - Non-terminal states encode their exit conditions structurally — through required `outputs:` artifacts and through transition `condition` / `exit_code` fields — not in prose inside `instructions`. Gating states must instead tell the human reader not to transition autonomously.
   209	   - Under `orchestrator` authority, every non-gating, non-final state resolves to a finite `agent_timeout` or `program_timeout` at some level of the timeout chain; see [Agents Specification — Timeout Requirement](rhei-agents.spec.md#timeout-requirement).
   210	
   211	10. **Write the YAML file.** Emit the file conforming to the YAML State Machine Format.
   212	
   213	11. **Validate with the CLI.** If the `rhei` CLI is available, run `rhei states --state-machine <path>` to verify the file parses correctly.
   214	
   215	## Examples
   216	
   217	> **Note:** The instructions in these examples include phrasing like "on
   218	> success, transition to X" for readability. In production state machines
   219	> run under `orchestrator` authority, encode that routing in transition
   220	> `condition` / `exit_code` fields and `outputs:` artifacts instead, and
   221	> keep `instructions` focused on the domain work (see Instructions Design
   222	> rule #2 above). The examples below are shown in the looser convention for
   223	> narrative clarity only.
   224	
   225	### Example 1: Data Pipeline Project
   226	
   227	**Input — specification:** "We process customer data through ingestion, transformation, validation, and publication stages. Bad data must be quarantined for manual review."
   228	
   229	**Input — teams:** "Data engineering builds and runs the pipeline. Data quality team reviews quarantined records. Product team signs off on publication to production."
   230	
   231	**Output:**
   232	
   233	```yaml
   234	name: data-pipeline
   235	version: 1.0
   236	
   237	states:
   238	  queued:
   239	    description: Data batch is registered and waiting to be processed.
   240	    instructions: |
   241	      Pick up when all Prior tasks are completed. Transition to ingesting
   242	      to begin processing.
   243	
   244	  ingesting:
   245	    description: Raw data is being loaded from source systems.
   246	    instructions: |
   247	      Load data from the configured source. Validate schema on ingestion.
   248	      On success, transition to transforming. On schema failure, transition
   249	      to quarantined.
   250	
   251	  transforming:
   252	    description: Data is being cleaned, enriched, and reshaped.
   253	    instructions: |
   254	      Apply transformation rules. Log row counts before and after.
   255	      On success, transition to validating.
   256	
   257	  validating:
   258	    description: Transformed data is checked against quality rules.
   259	    instructions: |
   260	      Run data quality checks (null rates, range checks, referential
   261	      integrity). On pass, transition to publication-review. On fail,
   262	      transition to quarantined.
   263	
   264	  quarantined:
   265	    description: Data failed quality checks and requires manual review.
   266	    instructions: |
   267	      Do not transition out of this state autonomously. Wait for the
   268	      data quality team to investigate, fix, and either return to
   269	      ingesting (reprocess) or cancel.
   270	
   271	  publication-review:
   272	    description: Product team reviews data before production publication.
   273	    instructions: |
   274	      Do not transition out of this state autonomously. Wait for
   275	      product team sign-off. On approval, transition to published.
   276	      On rejection, transition to transforming for rework.
   277	
   278	  published:
   279	    description: Data is live in production.
   280	    instructions: |
   281	      Terminal state. Do not modify.
   282	    final: true
   283	
   284	  cancelled:
   285	    description: Processing abandoned.
   286	    instructions: |
   287	      Terminal state. Skip entirely.
   288	    final: true
   289	
   290	transitions:
   291	  - from: queued
   292	    to: ingesting
   293	    description: Begin data processing
   294	  - from: ingesting
   295	    to: transforming
   296	    description: Ingestion succeeded, proceed to transformation
   297	  - from: ingesting
   298	    to: quarantined
   299	    description: Ingestion failed schema validation
   300	  - from: transforming
   301	    to: validating
   302	    description: Transformation complete, run quality checks
   303	  - from: validating
   304	    to: publication-review
   305	    description: Quality checks passed, ready for product review
   306	  - from: validating
   307	    to: quarantined
   308	    description: Quality checks failed
   309	  - from: quarantined
   310	    to: ingesting
   311	    description: Data quality team approved reprocessing
   312	  - from: publication-review
   313	    to: published
   314	    description: Product team approved publication
   315	  - from: publication-review
   316	    to: transforming
   317	    description: Product team requested rework
   318	  - from: "*"
   319	    to: cancelled
   320	    description: Processing abandoned at any stage
   321	
   322	profiles:
   323	  default:
   324	    initial: queued
   325	    allowed:
   326	      - queued
   327	      - ingesting
   328	      - transforming
   329	      - validating
   330	      - quarantined
   331	      - publication-review
   332	      - published
   333	      - cancelled
   334	
   335	node_policy:
   336	  root: default
   337	  default: default
   338	```
