   460	
   461	## Relationship to Other Roles
   462	
   463	| Role | Relationship |
   464	|------|-------------|
   465	| **Plan Writer** | Uses the state machine produced by this role. References it via `**States:** <name>` in the plan header. |
   466	| **Plan Worker** | Executes tasks using the states and transitions defined by this role. Follows the `instructions` field on each state. |
   467	| **Reviewer** | Review states in the machine define what the reviewer checks and how they advance work. |
   468	| **Human Operator** | Gating states designed by this role define where human judgment is required. |
   469	
   470	The state machine writer runs **before** the plan writer. The plan writer consumes the YAML file; it does not design workflows.
   471	
   472	## When to Use a Custom State Machine
   473	
   474	Use the default `rhei` state machine when:
   475	- The project follows a standard agent workflow (implement, review, complete).
   476	- There are no domain-specific phases or team handoffs.
   477	- The plan is small and does not need specialized gates.
   478	
   479	Use a custom state machine when:
   480	- The project has domain-specific phases (data stages, compliance gates, deployment tiers).
   481	- Multiple teams are involved with distinct approval authorities.
   482	- The workflow has non-trivial branching (retry loops, conditional paths, escalation chains).
   483	- Automated callbacks should fire on specific transitions.
   484	- The default states don't capture the project's real workflow.
   485	
   486	## File Placement
   487	
   488	State machine YAML files should be placed in the project at a conventional location:
   489	
   490	- `docs/states.yaml` — for projects with a single state machine.
   491	- `docs/states/<name>.yaml` — for projects with multiple state machines.
   492	
   493	Plans normally pick up a sibling or workspace-root `states.yaml`
   494	automatically when they declare `**States:** <name>`. The YAML file's
   495	`name` must match that declaration. Use `--state-machine <path>` when you
   496	need to override the conventional auto-discovered file, for example when
   497	reusing one shared machine from a non-standard location.
   498	
   499	## Related Specifications
   500	
   501	- [Plan Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md) — formal grammar and semantic constraints
   502	- [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) — default state machine format
   503	- [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) — YAML schema, callbacks, and transition system
   504	- [How Rhei Is Used](rhei-usage.spec.md) — roles, coordination patterns, and agent workflows

 succeeded in 757ms:
   750	### Artifact Enforcement
   751	
   752	State artifact contracts (see [States Specification — Artifact Contracts](rhei-states.spec.md#artifact-contracts) for the schema) are enforced around transitions:
   753	
   754	1. Before entering a target state, the runtime resolves `target.inputs` and
   755	   rejects the transition if any required input file does not exist.
   756	2. After `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks complete, but before the state write
   757	   is committed, the runtime resolves `source.outputs` and rejects the
   758	   transition if any required output file does not exist.
   759	3. `rhei complete` is subject to the same output checks as `rhei transition`.
   760	4. In v1, enforcement is file-existence only. Content validation is out of
   761	   scope.
   762	
   763	This makes artifact production and consumption part of the state-machine
   764	contract instead of a convention in free-form instructions.
   765	
   766	### Wildcard Semantics
   767	
   768	The special value `"*"` in the `from` field matches any state with these rules:
   769	- Matches any state **except** final states (states with `final: true`)
   770	- Specific transitions take precedence over wildcard transitions
   771	- A transition from a final state is always forbidden, even with wildcards
   772	
   773	Wildcards are optional. When a machine omits wildcards, only explicitly declared transitions are valid. Engines must not synthesize wildcard transitions; if cancellation from a particular state is desired, it must be declared explicitly (as the default `rhei` machine does).
   774	
   775	### Callback Declaration
   776	
   777	There are two valid ways to declare callbacks on transitions:
   778	
   779	**1. Platform-prefixed inline identifiers.** The `on_leave`/`on_enter` value includes a platform prefix (`cli:`, `js:`, `py:`, `java:`) followed by the implementation reference. No separate `callbacks:` mapping is needed. Use this when the machine targets a single platform or when each transition has a single implementation.
   780	
   781	```yaml
   782	transitions:
   783	  - from: pending
   784	    to: running
   785	    on_leave: cli:validate_preconditions    # Bash function
   786	    on_enter: js:startWork                  # JavaScript function
   787	```
   788	
   789	**2. Logical names with a `callbacks:` mapping.** The `on_leave`/`on_enter` values use platform-agnostic logical names. A top-level `callbacks:` section maps each logical name to platform-specific implementations. Use this when the same machine must work across multiple platforms.
   790	
   791	```yaml
   792	transitions:
   793	  - from: pending
   794	    to: active
   795	    on_leave: prepare_activation   # Logical name, resolved via callbacks:
   796	
   797	callbacks:
   798	  cli:
   799	    prepare_activation: ./handlers.sh:prepare_activation
   800	  nodejs:
   801	    prepare_activation: ./handlers.js:prepareActivation
   802	  python:
   803	    prepare_activation: handlers:prepare_activation
   804	```
   805	
   806	Both models are valid. They must not be mixed within a single transition (a callback value is either prefixed or logical, not both). When both a prefix and a `callbacks:` mapping exist for the same name, the prefix takes precedence.
   807	
   808	### Callback Mappings
   809	
   810	Platform-specific callback mappings allow the same logical callback name to resolve to different implementations:
   811	
   812	```yaml
   813	callbacks:
   814	  <platform>:
   815	    <callback-name>: <implementation-path>
   816	```
   817	
   818	Platform identifiers must match `Environment.platform` values:
   819	- `cli`: Command-line execution with bash functions
   820	- `nodejs`: JavaScript/TypeScript via NAPI
   821	- `python`: Python via PyO3 bindings
   822	- `java`: Java via JNI
   823	
   824	### Error Handling Configuration
   825	
   826	```yaml
   827	error_handling:
   828	  on_enter_failure:
   829	    - <action>              # Actions to take when on_enter callback fails
   830	  on_leave_rejection:
   831	    - <action>              # Actions to take when on_leave callback rejects
   832	```
   833	
   834	---
   835	
   836	## Examples
   837	
   838	> The examples in this section focus on state definitions, transitions, and
   839	> callback wiring. For readability they omit the top-level `profiles` and
   840	> `node_policy` blocks that a complete state machine YAML must declare. See
   841	> the [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md#profiles) for the full
   842	> profile and node-policy model and the
   843	> [reference machine](states.yaml) for a complete example.
   844	
   845	### Example 1: YAML State Machine Definition with Transitions
   846	
   847	This extends the existing [`states.yaml`](states.yaml) format to include formal transitions and callbacks:
   848	
   849	```yaml
   850	# states-with-transitions.yaml
   851	name: ci-pipeline-states
   852	version: 2.0
   853	
   854	states:
   855	  draft:
   856	    description: Task is being planned
   857	
   858	  pending:
   859	    description: Task ready to start
   860	
   861	  in-progress:
   862	    description: Task currently being worked on
   863	
   864	  human-review:
   865	    description: Awaiting human approval
   866	    gating: true
   867	
   868	  agent-review:
   869	    description: Automated validation in progress
   870	
   871	  completed:
   872	    description: Task finished successfully
   873	    final: true
   874	
   875	  cancelled:
   876	    description: Task abandoned
   877	    final: true
   878	
   879	# Explicit transition rules - any transition not listed here is FORBIDDEN.
   880	# This includes callback redirects: a nextState override must correspond to
   881	# a declared transition from the current state.
   882	transitions:
   883	  - from: draft
   884	    to: pending
   885	    description: Task planning is complete and ready for execution
   886	    on_leave: validate_task_ready      # Called when leaving 'draft'
   887	    on_enter: notify_task_pending      # Called when entering 'pending'
   888	
   889	  - from: pending
   890	    to: in-progress
   891	    description: Work begins on the task
   892	    on_leave: acquire_resources
   893	    on_enter: start_work_timer
   894	
   895	  - from: in-progress
   896	    to: human-review
   897	    description: Task requires human approval before completion
   898	    on_leave: package_for_review
   899	    on_enter: notify_reviewers
   900	
   901	  - from: in-progress
   902	    to: agent-review
   903	    description: Task requires automated validation before completion
   904	    on_leave: prepare_validation_context
   905	    on_enter: run_automated_checks
   906	
   907	  - from: human-review
   908	    to: in-progress
   909	    description: Reviewer requested changes, task returns to active work
   910	    on_leave: collect_feedback
   911	    on_enter: apply_review_changes
   912	
   913	  - from: human-review
   914	    to: completed
   915	    description: Human reviewer approved the task
   916	    on_leave: finalize_approval
   917	    on_enter: record_completion
   918	
   919	  - from: agent-review
   920	    to: in-progress
   921	    description: Automated checks found issues requiring fixes
   922	    on_leave: report_validation_issues
   923	    on_enter: apply_fixes
   924	
   925	  - from: agent-review
   926	    to: completed
   927	    description: Automated validation passed successfully
   928	    on_leave: archive_validation_results
   929	    on_enter: record_completion
   930	
   931	  # Any state can be cancelled (wildcard transition)
   932	  - from: "*"
   933	    to: cancelled
   934	    description: Task is abandoned and will not be completed
   935	    on_leave: cleanup_resources
   936	    on_enter: log_cancellation
   937	
   938	# Wildcard Semantics:
   939	# - "*" matches any state EXCEPT final states (states with `final: true`)
   940	# - Specific transitions take precedence over wildcard transitions
   941	# - A transition from a final state is always forbidden, even with wildcards
   942	```
